	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hmm... Perhaps then Bugs Bunny's Birthday Blowout was coded in C or BASIC then, haha (seriously, WTF is the frame rate in that game all about?).
<br />
<br />Oh, good old Oregon Trail. I don't think I played the first one ever; when I was in elementary school we actually had Oregon Trail 2. But judging from what I see in the video, I'll have to side with tokumaru on this. A text adventure like Oregon Trail would be pretty easy to make in BASIC, and even if the thing runs at 20 FPS, you don't notice because there's nothing really going on visually.
<br />
<br />Also, I'm sure linking together routines written in ASM with a language like BASIC is a lot less inefficient than coding the whole thing in BASIC. So it doesn't seem like Oregon Trail proves much about coding games for old consoles in BASIC/C. I'm not saying it's impossible, I'm just saying that I have yet to see proof (I'm sure there is proof, somewhere) that coding in C for the NES (or older consoles) is a good idea.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


